A young woman wathced a sage drawing water from the village well. Slowly, hand over hand, the old man pulled up the wooden bucket of water. After some time, the young woman left and returned with a pulley, and excitedly explained how to use it, and how easy it would be to draw water by cranking the handle. The old man refused: "Were I  to use a device like this, my mind would congratulate itself on being so clever, and then I would quit putting my heart into what I was doing... If I don't put my heart and my whole body into my work, my work will become joyless. And how, then, do you thinkg the water would taste?"
--- Zen Story
